{
  "query": "What factors influence the success of chemical control for invasive plants, considering examples from skunk cabbage and water primrose management?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across examples, herbicide choice strongly affects outcomes: for skunk cabbage, one UK study reported both glyphosate and 2,4\u2011D amine killed all plants, while another UK study found 2,4\u2011D amine at 9 L/ha eradicated skunk cabbage but glyphosate only limited growth (ID: 1102). For water primrose, triclopyr TEA at 0.25% killed 100% of young cultivated plants in a lab study, glyphosate achieved 97% mortality with a non\u2011oil sticking agent and 100% with TopFilm in a UK field study, and halosulfuron\u2011methyl significantly reduced coverage without apparent toxicity to rice (IDs: 1139). Adjuvants and formulation influence efficacy: adding specific sticking agents (non\u2011oil vs TopFilm) altered water primrose mortality from 97% to 100% (ID: 1139). Application context matters: plant age (young plants) and setting (laboratory vs field; presence of rice crop) were linked to different effectiveness and selectivity outcomes (ID: 1139). Integrating chemical applications with other methods can affect results: glyphosate plus the surfactant Cygnet\u2011Plus followed by mechanical removal achieved a 75% kill rate of water primrose in California, and a broader program combining herbicide, physical removal, native plant promotion, and mulching reduced Peruvian primrose\u2011willow coverage by 85\u201390% in Australia (ID: 1140).",
